INSERT INTO `policy_details` VALUES (1,'2','sub_control_policy','<h6>ISO 27001:2013 standard copy has been provided by MSCI.</h6><h6>ISO 27001:2022 standard copy to be developed internally and uploaded.</h6><p><br></p>',NULL,'2025-02-17 14:56:26'),(2,'1','linked_control_policy','<div class=\\\"clause-container\\\">\r\n                <h5><b>Background and context to our organization and its products/services</b></h5>\r\n<h6><span style=\\\"font-weight: normal;\\\"><b>Organization purpose</b></span></h6>\r\n<ul><li>Our purpose is to conduct supply chain audits for clients that \r\nare based globally.&nbsp; We review historic financial transactions between \r\nclients and their vendors, including contracts, pricing terms and \r\nconditions, vendor billing, and client AP transactions. </li><li>For\r\n the purpose of our audit projects research cases are uploaded to \r\nTracker which is a part of a larger system called ThunderCloud (a\r\n web application developed in-house). Audit team pursues the cases using \r\nTracker system.&nbsp; This system contains vendor contact information along \r\nwith other detail necessary to aid research activity such as notes and \r\ncall logs. User can also attach documents such as invoice copies, \r\npurchase order copies, email trails and so on for the record.</li><li>The audit team comprises of analysts, auditors, lead auditors and audit managers.<br>&nbsp;</li></ul>\r\n<p>The internal and external issues noted below have been developed \r\nthrough workshops and interaction with team members as well as \r\nconsidering the reason behind the requirements for controls and policies\r\n outlined in annex A of the standard (i.e. nudging us to think about the\r\n potential risks and issues given our purpose and context). This&nbsp;list \r\nalong with the other relevant requirements in the core standard&nbsp;then \r\ninforms the risk identification, evaluation, analysis and treatment \r\nundertaken in accordance with&nbsp;(6.1)&nbsp;which then leads onto the creation and implementation of appropriate policies and controls for our ISMS.</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<h5><strong>Internal Issues that might affect the intended outcome for the ISMS</strong></h5>\r\n<p><strong>Information (&amp; related Assets)</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li>Cases loaded into the Tracker system has information such as \r\nvendor name, address, contact information, amount and currency of \r\ntransaction (invoice number, invoice date, invoice amount, invoice \r\ncurrency as well as payment amount, payment currency and payment date).&nbsp;\r\n Additionally user can attach documents such as copies of invoices and \r\npurchase orders or even email trails.</li><li><em>Audit specific \r\ncontracts and documents such as agreement with vendors, audit letter, \r\nletter of authorization, purchase order and so forth.</em></li><li><em>Research case specific data and attachments.</em></li><li><em>Case notes and call logs.</em></li><li><em>Internal Issues</em><ul><li>User\r\n Management (who has access to what) - IT admin grants access to systems\r\n such as Trackers, HR portal, MRS.&nbsp; User access level determines \r\nfunctionality available.</li><li>Asset management - Only in3 owned \r\nassets should be used for work purpose.&nbsp; There should be an active \r\ninventory which can indicate assets and their allocated users.&nbsp; Client \r\nassets need to be specially protected and kept separate from other \r\ncompany owned assets.</li><li>Secure access -&nbsp;Only users with logins \r\ncan access the system.&nbsp; System needs to be logged into to gain access to\r\n various sub systems and functionalities.&nbsp; People should be able to \r\naccess only that information which is relevant to their duty.&nbsp; Employees\r\n should not have direct access to HR files, IT inventory, networking \r\nresources and so forth.&nbsp; Physical access should be secured and \r\nmonitored.&nbsp; Access to ThunderCloud should be secured, monitored and \r\naccess should be role based.<br>Employees may be allowed to work from \r\nhome under certain circumstances for a limited time.&nbsp; Employee \r\nmonitoring and use of VPN is important for work-from-home situation.</li><li>Secure\r\n data storage (how can the data be accessed who can directly access \r\nit).&nbsp; Data classification and labeling needs to be followed to tell \r\nconfidential information from other types of information.&nbsp; Employees \r\nshould be able to access only that data for which they can demonstrate \r\n\\\'need to know\\\'.&nbsp; Data should be backed up and stored away in a secure \r\narea.&nbsp; Data encryption should ensure confidentiality is maintained in \r\ncase of a security event.</li></ul></li></ul>\r\n<p><strong>People</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li><em>Analysts, Auditors, Leads, Audit Managers, Management and IT have access to Tracker.&nbsp; <br></em></li><li><em>Client has read only access to specific information via another system Client Reporting System (CRS).</em></li><li><em>Management,\r\n Audit Managers and Auditors have read only access to MRS which pulls \r\nspecific information from Trackers on a weekly basis for reporting \r\npurpose.&nbsp; Client and Analysts do not have access to this system.</em></li><li><em>User entry/exit procedures<br></em></li><li><em>User monitoring<br></em></li><li><em>Mode of working - work from home, contractor, intern, full employee</em></li></ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>Organization</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li><em>hierarchy, roles and responsibilities</em><ul><li>CEO -&gt; \r\nVice President -&gt; Director of Client Relationship and Audit Managers,\r\n IT Manager and Manager of Client Relationship  -&gt; Audit Leads -&gt; \r\nAuditors -&gt; Analysts</li><li>Security coordinators are selected from among existing employees from Ops and/or IT.</li></ul></li><li><em>Physical locations: Boulder, Colorado USA and Lucknow, Uttar Pradesh, India.</em><br><ul><li>Bulk of operations is conducted from Lucknow office. Over 90% of employee-base is in Lucknow.</li><li>Employee monitoring helps to ensure that work is tracked regularly.</li></ul></li><li>Culture and motive<ul><li>Information,\r\n Insight and Integrity - We are in people business and treat our \r\norganization as a family unit.&nbsp; We believe in valuing our relationship \r\nwith clients and recognize that we approach as people and not just as a \r\ncompany.&nbsp; For this reason, we strive to adhere to government and \r\nregional policies especially pertaining to security of data, such as \r\nGDPR.</li></ul></li></ul>\r\n<p><strong>Product/Service</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li><em>audit services - It is imperative that confidentiality of \r\nclient data is maintained.&nbsp; Clients are increasingly demanding \r\ncompliance to business practices and compliance to GDPR or related \r\nguidelines to ensure security of their data.<br></em></li></ul>\r\n<p><strong>Processes</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li><em>How is data received?&nbsp; Where is it stored?&nbsp; How is it \r\nprocessed and used?&nbsp; We should be able to demonstrate that we have \r\nsufficient controls over these activities.</em></li><li>We should be able to demonstrate safe data practices and that we have policies to enforce those.</li><li><em>Processes need to be documented.&nbsp; For example, every project has a workplan to track various activities within it.</em></li><li><em>Use of 3rd party - we do not use sub-contractors or 3rd parties for processing client data.<br></em></li><li>Software\r\n used in data processing - We should be able to demonstrate that there \r\nare policies to dictate approved software.&nbsp; For example, software \r\ninstallation policy outlines the technologies which are acceptable such \r\nas MySQL, PHP, Javascript, Microsoft Office products, WinZip, etc.</li><li>Data\r\n checking for potential GDPR breach and actions taken - We need to \r\ndemonstrate that personal information is identified and such data is \r\npurged.&nbsp; We should demonstrate active compliance to GDPR by protecting \r\npersonal data.&nbsp; Unless a project absolutely requires some personal data,\r\n all such data should be deleted and client should be notified.</li><li>We\r\n need to ensure that access to systems, projects and data is role based \r\nwith a demonstrable \\\'need to know\\\'.&nbsp; For example, analysts cannot change\r\n workplan and neither can they upload or assign cases in Trackers.&nbsp; No \r\none other than CEO and IT should have access to User Management, web \r\nserver, etc.</li><li>There should be a clear entry exit procedure to \r\nensure that all necessary steps are taken with regards to \r\ngranting/revoking user access, asset allocation/retrieval etc.</li></ul>\r\n<p><br><strong>Systems</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li><em></em><em>We should have a robust asset management process to\r\n ensure that we can track each company owned asset as well as its \r\nusers.&nbsp; For example, TechTracker system of ThunderCloud is used for \r\nasset management.</em></li><li><em>We should be able to identify users \r\nof a system based upon their roles.&nbsp; For example, client management \r\nsystem of ThunderCloud is accessible to CEO, VP and sales team; \r\noperations personnel should not have access to this.&nbsp; Web server is \r\naccessible to CEO and IT only.</em></li><li>ThunderCloud has modules for\r\n various purposes: TechTracker and Admin for IT, Trackers for Ops, \r\nUniverse for sales, in3HR for all employees and HR.&nbsp; MRS for Ops \r\nmanagers, team leads and upper management.&nbsp; Access should be role based.</li></ul>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<h5>External Issues that might affect the intended outcome for the ISMS</h5>\r\n<p><strong>Political</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li><em>Clients, especially in Europe, are increasingly pressing for GDPR compliance. <strong><br></strong></em></li><li>Clients are requiring demonstration of secure practices.&nbsp; For this reason we are going for ISO certification.</li><li>We need to ensure that we comply with local government policies.</li></ul>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<p><strong>Technological</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li><em>Changes in technology can affect the way we conduct \r\nbusiness.&nbsp; Current trend is pushing for SAAS which can render many \r\nexisting technologies obsolete.&nbsp; This would mean additional costs and \r\nchanges to processes.<br></em></li><li>With data security becoming \r\ncrucial, we would need to invest in monitoring software, VPN software, \r\nand other technologies as well as compliance audits.</li><li>We have a \r\nVPS server hosted by 3rd party based in US (Hostwinds).&nbsp; We need to take\r\n into consideration issues pertaining to secure data transfer and online\r\n data storage as well as secure access.&nbsp; We did away with FTP and \r\nimplemented SFTP to enable only secure file transfer.&nbsp; We have \r\nconfigured the web server to allow only HTTPS for web access. Data \r\nbackup has to be taken regularly to guard against sudden and \r\ncatastrophic failure of the server; we should be able to restore \r\nfunctionality using the backup.</li><li>Access is lost when server is \r\ndown.&nbsp; Access to mails, SFTP and web portal would be lost when server is\r\n down.&nbsp; We should be able to use alternate communication channels and \r\nhave offline working capabilities until the server is back and running \r\nagain.</li><li>Outdated OS or Apache web server can result in \r\ninaccessibility or code incompatibility resulting in a huge amount of \r\ncode tweaking.</li></ul>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<p><strong>Legislative/Regulatory</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li><em>EU and UK GDPR</em></li><li><em>The Companies Act, 2013 (India)</em></li><li><em><em>Indian IT law (<strong>Information Technology Act, 2000</strong>)</em></em></li><li><em>US corporate law</em></li><li><em>Colorado Privacy Act</em></li></ul>\r\n<p>We should have knowledge of these to ensure that we are compliant.<br></p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Environmental</strong></p>\r\n<ul><li><em>Data is backed up regularly (daily, weekly and monthly) at \r\nthe server.&nbsp; In case of a catastrophe they should be able to get the \r\nwebsite back and up within a couple hours.&nbsp; At our end we backup the \r\ndatabase and code however attachments are not regularly backed up.</em></li></ul>            </div><p><br></p>',NULL,'2025-02-17 15:33:47'),(3,'2','linked_control_policy','<h4>Interested Parties<br></h4><p></p><p>Internal Parties<br></p><table><tbody><tr><th><b>Interested Party</b><br></th><th><b>Needs</b><br></th><th><b>Expectations</b></th></tr><tr><td>Upper Management (CEO, VP, Managers)<br></td><td>Commitment to infosec.<br>Planning of business operations.<br>Reports and updates.<br></td><td>Ensure ISMS is up to date.<br>Management review meetings.<br>Procedures are followed as documented.<br>Establish plans and followup.<br>Have regular meetings.<br></td></tr><tr><td>Middle Management (Team Leads, Auditors)<br></td><td>Operations follow secure data procedures.<br>Manage day to day project activities.<br><br></td><td>Regular infosec trainings, monitoring and control.<br>Team meetings are held regularly.<br></td></tr><tr><td>Operations Staff<br></td><td>Training related to Infosec<br>Job Description is clearly defined.<br>Training and feedback.<br></td><td>Employees should attend infosec trainings and pass evaluation.<br>HR should communicate JD at the time of hiring and promotion.<br>Performance appraisals, training and evaluations are timely conducted.</td></tr><tr><td>IT and Security<br></td><td>Protection of personal data<br>Resources are provided timely<br><br></td><td>Gain knowledge of regulations such as GDPR and safe data practices.<br>Regular internal audits.<br>Operations IT needs are evaluated and communicated timely.<br></td></tr></tbody></table><p>External Parties<br></p><table><tbody><tr><td><b>Interested Party</b><br></td><td><b>Needs</b><br></td><td><b>Expectations</b></td></tr><tr><td>Client</td><td>On-time delivery of services.<br>Protection of confidential data.<br>Complaint resolution.<br></td><td>Followup and meetings to ensure all requests are addressed.<br>Ensure infosec policy exists and is followed.<br>Customer complaint and feedback mechanism.<br></td></tr><tr><td>External Service Provider<br></td><td>Identification of provider is carried out by departmental manager.<br></td><td>Upper management approves the service provider.<br></td></tr><tr><td>Visitor</td><td>Information regarding services<br></td><td>Website should provide information regarding services.<br></td></tr><tr><td>Government Authorities and Regulatory Bodies<br></td><td>Compliance to legal requirements.<br></td><td>Awareness of laws and regulations.<br>Regulations are followed.<br></td></tr><tr><td>ISO Certification Body<br></td><td> Effective implementation of ISO standards with all relevant clauses in the organization | Audits reports<br></td><td>Maintenance of ISO certifications.<br>Reconnaissance audits. </td></tr></tbody></table><br>',NULL,'2025-02-17 15:39:58'),(4,'3','linked_control_policy','<div class=\\\"clause-container\\\">\r\n                <div class=\\\"wysiwyg_formatted p_s\\\">\r\n      <h4><span style=\\\"font-weight: normal;\\\"><b>Scope<br></b></span></h4><h6>Security of data within ThunderCloud program and process.</h6>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Address<br></b></p><h6>in3corp corporate office<br>1750 30th Street, Suite #216<br>Boulder, CO 80301</h6>\r\n<p><b>International operations<br></b></p><h6>SP20, Sector C, Aliganj, Lucknow, U.P., India</h6>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<p><b>Non-applicable clauses</b>: <br></p><h6>A.14.2.7 Outsourced   Software Development</h6></div>            </div><p><br></p>',NULL,'2025-02-17 15:42:44'),(5,'4','linked_control_policy','<h4><b>What we do</b></h4><p>This completed ISMS.online environment is made up of the following core components for operating, maintaining and improving the organization\\\'s ISMS:<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This Policies and Controls area and Statement of Applicability <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Risk &amp; Treatment area<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Interested Parties map<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The register of Applicable Legislation<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Asset Inventory <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Management Review Board <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Audit Programme <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Corrective Actions and Improvements track<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Security Incident Management track<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Staff communications area<br><br>Each area is reviewed and updated in line with A.5.1.2: Review of the policies for information security and A.18.2 Information security reviews. improvements are managed in line with 10 Improvement.<br><br>An audit trail of all changes is clearly visible in each area and the Linked Work tool is uses to show relationships between individual parts of the ISMS.<br><br>This ISMS is designed and developed to allow us to create, collaborate, control and communicate in line with the clause and control requirements. Automatically giving us a contribution towards:<br><br><b>Clauses<br></b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 5.3: Organisation roles, responsibilities and authorities<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 6.1.3: Statement of Applicability<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 7.1: Resources<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 7.2: Competence<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 7.3: Awareness<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 7.4: Communication<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 7.5: Documented information<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 8: Operation<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 9.1: Monitoring &amp; review<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10.2: Continuous improvement <br><br><b>Controls</b><br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A.5.1.1: Policies for info security approved by management, published and communicated<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A.5.1.2: Review of policies â€“ review at planned intervals, or significant changes<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A.6.1.1: Roles &amp; responsibilities<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A.6.1.2: Segregation of duties<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A.7.2.2: Awareness, education &amp; training<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A.18.2: Independent and technical review of info sec at planned intervals</p>',NULL,'2025-02-17 15:45:37'),(6,'5','linked_control_policy','<p>Our upper management has taken an active role to ensure that our practices are in-line with client expectations especially pertaining to data regulation policies such as GDPR.&nbsp; Security coordinator role was created, designated personnel were trained and various procedures and policies were introduced.&nbsp; Regular internal audits, monitoring and trainings are conducted to mitigate potential risk situations. <br><br>The organization has instilled in its employees to keep security at the forefront, and to make it an integral part of their DNA.<br><br>Operations has demonstrated active compliance from time to time by identifying issues, taking corrective actions and bringing it to the knowledge of the clients. &nbsp;<br><br>We demonstrate leadership and commitment with respect to the ISMS by:<br></p><ul><li>A) Ensuring that the ISMS and IS objectives are established.</li><li>B) Ensuring the integration of the ISMS into the organisation\\\'s processes.</li><li>C) Ensuring resources for the ISMS are available.</li><li>D) Communicating the importance of the ISMS.</li><li>E) Ensuring the ISMS achieves its intended outcomes is demonstrated through the commitment of the leadership and involvement of senior management team for creation and implementation of the ISMS itself.</li><li>F) CEO and Senior Management have taken active role in updating existing policies</li><li>H) Supporting other relevant management roles to demonstrate their leadership as it applies to their areas of responsibility. As our organisation continues to grow other individuals will be given the opportunity to take leadership roles in specific areas.</li></ul>',NULL,'2025-02-17 15:46:31'),(7,'6','linked_control_policy','<h6>The organizational Information Security Policy is attached under <a href=\\\"https://platform.r3.isms.online/projects/22446/deliverables/912239\\\">A5.1.1</a> and can be shared with interested parties as necessary.</h6>\r\n<h6>All subordinate policies and controls adhere to this policy and are \r\ncontained within this online ISMS environment and can be made available \r\nas specific documents where required.</h6><p><br></p>',NULL,'2025-02-17 16:07:27'),(8,'7','linked_control_policy','<h6>Relevant JDs are attached with this page.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>This section summarizes the roles of upper management and people responsible for ISMS.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Miguel Zavala is the CEO of in3corp and is a key stakeholder of the \r\ncompany.&nbsp; He has a direct interest in ensuring that the organization \r\npasses client expectations in flying colors.&nbsp; He is the key decision \r\nmaker and approves decisions for operations, Information Systems and \r\nfinances.&nbsp; CEO is the head of Management Review Board of ISMS as well as\r\n the CISO, and leads quarterly Management Review Board meetings, ensures\r\n internal audit takes places annually within 3 months before external \r\naudit.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Nick Brown as Vice President is also a party of interest being a part\r\n of upper management. He is also part of ISMS Management Review Board \r\nwithin which he is responsible for ensuring that all operative staff are\r\n properly trained and following all protocols associated with the ISMS. <br></h6>\r\n<h6>Jaya Poonja is in charge of all HR related activities. She is \r\nresponsible for ensuring background checks, on-boarding and exit of \r\nemployees are properly documented, as well as other HR tasks as they \r\nrelate to the ISMS.&nbsp; She is also part of Management Review Board.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Siddharth Asthana and Shriya Raghuvanshi are designated Security \r\nCoordinators and are responsible for reporting on the performance of the\r\n system to upper management and they are also part of ISMS Management \r\nReview Board.&nbsp; They own actions pertaining to maintenance of ISMS \r\nsystem, such as update of control points, recording and tracking \r\nincidents, recording and tracking compliance and improvements.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Siddharth Asthana has been designated for reporting on the performance of ISMS specifically involving improvements to top management.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Siddharth Asthana and Shriya Raghuvanshi are the designated Data \r\nProtection Officers (security coordinators) and lead on aspects relating\r\n to the protection of privacy and personal data including personally \r\nidentifiable information (PII) in compliance with the GDPR.<br></h6>\r\n\r\n<h6>Each control and policy area within this environment has an owner who\r\n is responsible for its updating and reporting for any proposed changes \r\nor amendments. They can allow other authorized staff to propose changes \r\nto the requirements, policies and controls. Authorized staff will have \r\ndirect team membership of this policies and controls environment.</h6>\r\n<h6>Any amendments to the ISMS requirements, policies and controls may \r\nget done dynamically, i.e. as the situation requires, or for more \r\nfundamental changes, after discussion and agreement with one or more \r\nrelevant upper management members (who in any event independently \r\napprove any policy change or are delegating approval in accordance with \r\nthe roles above).</h6><p><br></p>',NULL,'2025-02-17 16:07:59'),(9,'1','inner_linked_control_policy','<h6>Internal and external risks have been identified, measured and \r\nassigned to relevant control points.&nbsp; Additional risks and threats if \r\nand when identified in future, would be assigned to relevant control \r\npoints.</h6>\r\n<h6>The&nbsp;risks &amp; treatments&nbsp;tool\r\n is&nbsp;used to map and treat risks identified from the analysis. It is&nbsp;also\r\n used to evidence activity and demonstrate links back to the controls \r\nand policies selected by the organization to address the risk threats \r\nand opportunities.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Risks identified are presented on Risk Map within Risks &amp; Treatments tool on the basis of their scores / reading.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Likelihood is rates as:<br></h6>\r\n<h6>1 - Very Low<br></h6>\r\n<h6>2 - Low<br></h6>\r\n<h6>3 - Medium<br></h6>\r\n<h6>4 - High<br></h6>\r\n<h6>5 - Very High<br></h6>\r\n\r\n<h6>Impact is the CIA with the highest value.&nbsp; Impact is rated as:<br></h6>\r\n<h6>0 - None<br></h6>\r\n<h6>1 - Insignificant<br></h6>\r\n<h6>2 - Minor<br></h6>\r\n<h6>3 - Moderate<br></h6>\r\n<h6>4 - Major<br></h6>\r\n<h6>5 - Severe<br></h6>\r\n\r\n<h6>Likelihood and Impact values are assigned to each risk depending upon\r\n what controls have been implemented. The intent is to lower the score \r\nas much as possible to, if possible, eliminate the risk.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Risks once rated/scored start appearing on the Risk Map with the \r\nlowest scored risks at the bottom left and the highest scoring on the \r\nupper right.&nbsp; Risk Map is a grid of 5 X 5 with Likelihood as the Y axis \r\nand Impact as the X axis.&nbsp; A risk with Impact 3 (moderate) and \r\nLikelihood 2 (low) would show in grid 3,2.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Grids are colored according to the risk score into four colors.&nbsp; Green being the lowest risks and black highest.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Risk review frequency depends upon the grid color in which the risk appears.<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Green - at least annually<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Yellow - at least half yearly<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Red - at least quarterly<br></h6>\r\n<h6>Black - at least monthly<br></h6>\r\n\r\n<h6>For detail regarding Risk Map please refer to attached document 6.1_Risk_Treatment_Methodology_-_ISMS.Online_-_V1.7.docx</h6><h6><br></h6>',NULL,'2025-02-17 16:11:14');
